{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17602157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17602157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:22:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:22:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15686"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.76,0,0.07,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56647"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8530"},{"type":"tags","id":"10114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a primary follicle, a primary oocyte is surrounded by a single layer of granulosa cells. Under the influence of follicle stimulating hormone and local paracrine factors, the granulosa cells proliferate and form multiple layers. The surrounding ovarian stromal cells differentiate into theca cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the structure that develops from a primary follicle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Secondary follicle","Antral follicle","Primordial follicle","Graafian follicle","Atretic follicle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary follicle\u003C/strong\u003E represents the next developmental stage after the primary follicle. It is characterized by multiple layers of granulosa cells and the presence of theca cells that have differentiated from the surrounding stroma. This structure precedes the development of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eantral follicle\u003C/strong\u003E, which is distinguished by the appearance of fluid-filled cavities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe developmental sequence cannot proceed backwards to form \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimordial follicles\u003C/strong\u003E, as these represent the initial stage of follicular development. The \u003Cstrong\u003EGraafian follicle\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mature pre-ovulatory stage, occurring much later in development. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eatretic follicle\u003C/strong\u003E represents a follicle undergoing programmed degeneration, which can occur at any stage of follicular development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary follicles develop into secondary follicles through granulosa cell proliferation and theca cell differentiation","The progression from primary to secondary follicle is an important step in follicular development before antrum formation"],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56647"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56647"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:33:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:39:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reprodu